<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-02-28T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-02-28T20:00:00-05:00" n="893" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d893">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/6394.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">American Ambassador</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-02-28T20:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 28, 1913—8 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>58. Your 46, February 26, 4 p.m. The Department perceives no reason to
                            doubt the usefulness of such unofficial activities undertaken upon its
                            own responsibility by the Embassy and always kept within the limits of
                            cautious circumspection.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Knox</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>